{"/service/ndnp/nmu/batch_nmu_austen_ver01/data/sn93061701/0041562685A/1920101501/0639.xml":{"full_text":"NEW MEXICO STATE RECORD\nSUBSCRIPTION $1.50\nSANTA FE, NEW MEXICO. FRIDAY, OCTOBER 15, 1920\nNUMBER 315\nCOLONIZING THE\nSUNSHINE VALLEY\nVolney T. Hoggat, editor of the\nGreat Divide, Denver's leading week\nly is in th? city on business In\nconnection with the colonization of\nthe Sunshine Valley in Taos coun\nty The 20,000 acres beintf colonized\n!y tin- Great Divide lie in a shal\nlow water tx.lt. Wells have been\ndug at various localities in the val\nley and clear, cool, soft and pure\nwater encountered in never failing\nquantities at depths of from eight\nto sixteen feet. This lert le level\nIan i can be bought for $30 n acrs\nand with the inexhaustible water\nsupply surpasses any land we know\nof in the western states.\n'laos county in which the land\nior colonization is located is hound\ned on the west by the Rio ur.tude.\non the east by the Red River from\nwhich mountain river this 20,01)0\nacres will have the first 200 cub c\nfect of water per second of tunc\nof its continuous flow dedicated to\nits perpetual use for irrigation. Also\nCabresto Creek which carr es near\nly one half the volume of Red River\nand of which it is a tributory. Al\nwater for irrigation have sources\nhigh n the Sangre de Cristo foun\ntains that flows toward and sinks\nin the valley, which is one of the\nsources of the underground water\nsupply, which lies at shallow depths.\nAlso 'Latir Creek that heads in the\nLatir peaks and runs the ytar a\nround through the lands being col\nonized. Homeseekers never overlook the\nvital .necessity of water, particularly\nin the semi arid west. Here we\nhave water for domestic purposes\nat shallow depths and water for ir\nrigation by gravity. The sources ol\nwatir for irrigation live source\nnearly one mile above the valley\nSunshine Valley has a slope from\nthe Carson National Forest, its\neastern boundary, to the R o Grandt\nsue miles west, of forty five f.ei\nto the mile The bed of the Can\nyon of the Rio Grande is 1)00 fee'\nbelow the surface of the valley. Tim\neliminates forever any seepage thai\nm ght be caused by continued irri\ngation. Furthermore the average rainfall\nin the Sunshine Valley for the past\nnine years as given out by the\nWeather Bureau at Virsylvia, Sun\nshine Valley, shows the mean vr\nage to be seventeen inches per year\nwith nearly ten inches of this rain\ntall during the growing season. July\nregisters the heaviest precipitat on\nwhile June shows the lowest. There\nwere only forty six cloudy days dur\ning the ytar 1919.\nAnd where is there a more ideal\nclimate than ill Sunshine Valley\n(anuary in the coldest month while\nthe hottest summer temperature has\nnever registered above 98F\nWith a salubrious climate, fertile\nand productive so I, water in abund\nance for domestic purposes and for\nirrigation, free national resources of\nwood, water and pasture on al sides\nof this valley what more can be said\nIt. S. ATTORNEY IN COAL\nCASES QUITS PALMER\nINDIANAPOLIS. Oct. 13 Dan W.\nSimms, special assistant attorney\ngeneral in the cases pending against\ncoal operators and officials of the\nUnited Mine Workers of America,\nindicted under the Lever act last\nwinter, has resigned, it became\nmi here today.\nMr. Simms while admitting that\nhe had lent his res gnation to at\ntorney general Palrm r at Washing\nton, declined to discuss the ca-e\nwhrn seen in Lafayette, Indiana. It\nis understood, however that Mr\nSimmt' resignation was due to a\ndisagreement with ihe attorney gen\neral over procedure ard evidence to\nbe used in the coal esses\nft is understood that Mr. Simms\nreceived a letter from Mr. Palmer a\nfw days ago p'aciinr certain re\nstrictions on the evidence to be used\nin the coal cases and th.it Mr. Simms\nre'ignation followe 1 c'os.v upon\nthe rtctipt of this letter .lust what\nthe restrictions in the letter were is\nnot known and Mr. Simms declined\nto discuss the case, at least until ac\ntion has been taken on his resigna\ntion. JOHNSON CAMPAIGNING\nFOR SENATOR HARDING\nCHICAGO. Oct. 13 Senator Hi\nram A. Johnson arrived in this city\ntoday to open a whirlwind campaign\nlor Senator Harding in the Central\nstates. Four dates were closed for\nthe California orator today. His\nf rst appearance will be on Wednes-i\nday at Toledo. Cleveland will be\nvisited the day after and he wiil\nspeak at Milwaukee Friday, and\nChicago on Saturday.\nJohnson's appearance is expectel\nittr thing! up politically, especially\nwhen he speaks in the home state of\nthe twi rival candidates.\nCOUNTY CAMPAIGN IN\nFULL SWING THIS WEEK\nThe Santa Fe county candidates\nheld a large meeting at San Ilde\ntoi.so Sunday afternoti, one at\nCHmavo Mottdav evenins sid an\nother at Santa Cruz Tresd.iy i t,\ning At every one of thes; M.et\nings Democnts afended and de\nclared that thev we'e going t) sup\nport the full Republiran ticket this\nyear.\nThis evening another meeting t\nTook.d for San 1 ueii'cnso\nLOS ANGELES BANKS TO\nFINANCE COTTON CROPS\nLOS ANGELES. Oct. 13 All ihe\nbinks of Los Angeles have joined\nin an arrangement to finance the\ncotton crops of California, Ar\nard NrT Mexico to the exlint of\n$200.000 according to an annoano -toent\ntoday by J. Dabney Day. vice\n(resident of the First National Bink.\nTHE FOREST SERVICE\nNEEDS MORE RANGERS\nCompetitive e xaminations for for\nest rangers wiil be held October 25,\n'ii New Mexico at Alamogordo, Al\nbuquerque, Magdalenat Santa Fe,\nSilver City, and Taos. Persons de\nsiring t0 take the examination may\nsecure application form 1312 from\nthe Civil Service Commission, Wash\nington, D. C, from the Forest Sup\nerv sor at any of the examination\nplaces above mentioned, or from the\nDistrict Forester, Albuquerque. The\nCommission urges that applicants\nsecure this form immediately\nThe work of the forest ranger is\nlargely out-doors, in mountainous\nforested regions, and men who like\nmounts n work, are willing to en\ndure hardship if necessary, and can\ntake care of themselves and their\nsaddle-horses in remote reg ons are\nwanted. Applicants must be able\nbodied,' and are required to pass a\nmedical examination; and must be\nbetween the ages of twenty-one and\nforty years. Persons entitled t\npreference because of military or\nnaval scrv ce are released fom aire\nrequirements. Rangers must be cap\nable ot performing such manual lab\nor as fighting forest fires, and\nbuilding cabins, trails, and telephone\nlines. They must have at least a\ncommon education, and know the ru\ndiments of compass surveying, tint\nber scal'ng and estimating, land\nlaws, and the livestock industry. A\ngood fund of common sense and\nsome experience in kindred lines of\nwork such as engineering or lumber-\nii'g, will materially help applicants.\nAppointees receive $1220, per year,\nand may be allowed after the f rst\nmonth the temporary increase of $20\nper month until June 30, 1920. In\nmost cases quarters are provided\nby the Government. Rangers atej\nrequired to furn sh saddle horses,'\ntwo being the usual requirement, but\nforage for necessary horses is furn-;\nishcd by the Government.\nBISHOPS LODGE BADLY\nDAMAGED BY FIRE\nYesterday morning the people ol\nSanta Fe were startled by the fire\nsiren and there was much conster\nnrtion when it was learned that the\nfire was at Bishops Lodge the beau\ntiful summer resort about two mil.;\nfrom the city. The city fire i\npayment responded to the call and\nwas soon on the ground and with a\nlarge number of volunteers worked\nhero cally to suppress the fire.\nThe fire, which was in one of the'\nmain buildings, was caused it is\nsaid by I defective flue. Bucket\nlines were organized and chemicals j\nused' very freely. At one time' u\nwas feared that at! of the building\nwas doomed but through the un\nceasing work of the volunteers the\nlarger part of the building tfas sav\ned. Several shots of dynam te were\nused and as there is no water system\nat the Lodge the volunteers are to\nbe commended in thrir excellent\n'work of saving part of the building\nIt is understood that most of the j\nloss was covered by insurance t\nRED CROSS PREPARES 1\nFOR FOURTH ROLL CALL\nEvery Red Cross Chapter n th 1\nstate of New Mexico has been asked\nby M is Gertrude Orr, manager of\nthe Red Cross Roll Call, scheduled I\nto take place between November 11 I\nand 25 to appoint a Roll Call Chair- j\nman and to make careful plans for\nan energetic Roll Call.\n\"The purpose of the Fourth Roll\nCall is not for primary funds, \"an- I\nnounced Miss Orr recently\", it is!\nto secure a large membership cam\nposed of people with an intelligent j\ninterest in the work of the Red\nCross, without which no organiza- j\nton, regardless of its a:ms, can'\nprogress. We want as wide-spread\nmembership as it is possible for e\nto enroll so that in each community\nthe greater percent of the citizens\nwill be R:d Cross members an(;\ntherefore interested and sympa- i\nthetic concerning the activities ot i\nthe Red Cross of Peace.\"\nMRS. BYNE ORGANIZING\nWOMEN IN COLFAX COUNTY\nRATON. N M, October 9 Mrs.;\nCharles M. Bayne has been elected 1\nb the R;publican County Central:\ncommittee as woman's chairman for'\nColfax county. She already has be\ngun work of organizing the \"repub\nlican women of fhe county and an\nactive campaign is to be mide to!\nenroll women in the republican par-j\nI\nSTRONG TICKET\nIN TAOS COUNTY\nTAOS. N. M Oct. 8 What is\nregarded as the strongest republt-;\ncan ticket ever made up in Taos\ncounty was completed by the county\nconvention in session here last n:ght.'\nRepublicans rt confident cf v;e\ntorr and peed ct a majority of from\n12\"0 to 1.400\nSUPRFMF mtlPT RFFIJFS TO\nRECONSIDER PROHIBITION\nWasHnirton. Oct. 11. The supreme,\ncorr tcdiv refused to rTonider !t\nJrr:s on rvf last June 7th. nir-j\nj,yr i-MVity of .fbe rtroiMti\"\"\namendment and provisions of t;f\nenforcement act. i I\ncKrr-ortinc affidavits that Mr.\nFubbell laid srio'ent hands nr-on Mr\nMontoya's danghter when fe e:ect\ned her from the office of the news-f-aper\nhav been filed bv J. P. J-rob-on.\nBonifac'o Apodaca, and Vera\nft Miss Mont-ya and Dr.'\nM. K VVytder he' atten-'n. physi\ncian have both filed affidavits rf\nher condition following the episode\non October ft,\nFrom the White House comes thri\nannouncement tht leadership on\nthe League of Nations issue has\nbecome imperative, and that Gov\nernor Cox's efforts require gn'dance.\nOFHCI4L NEWS OF\nTHE PRESENT WEEK.\nR E. Brock of Springer asked fur\nS second feet from the Cimarron\nrtV'T to use in irrigating 1t0 acres nt\nland.\nJ. S Turnbull of New York ask.\nfor 20 second feet from Taylor creek\nwhich he w 11 use for milling and\nconcentrating.\nThe Stern Cattle company tiled\napplication for a permit to use one\nhalf second feet from the Middle or\nSouth Ponil for irrigation.\nAmong those asking for a water\nappropriation were Pound Bros, of\nChama. They ask\"491 second feet\nfrom the Chama River to irrigate\n285 acres and for domestic purpose!\nThe Major Oil company of Dela\nware filed foreign corporation\nstatement with the corporation\nc mmisson. $5,000 of the $1.0iKU\nworth of stock has been subscribed.\nWilliam P. Harris of Vaughn is the\nNew Mexico statutory agent.\nThe Silver City Copper company\nI as changed its name to the Ameri\ncan Flnospar corporat on and reduc\ned its capital from $2.500000 to $:0tl.\n'X! which is divided into 2.5O0.00H\nstares of the value of 20 cents each\nThe president of the company is E.\nI) l,id stone of Silver City.\nThe Rocky Mountain Rod and\nCoin club has capitalized for $50000\n$3,000 of which has been subscribed,\naccording to art cles of incorpora\ntion fil?d with the commission. The\nincorporators are: W. K. McKinlev\nf as Vegas, 10 shares; George H\nHunker, Las Vegas, 10; J. L. Swart-'\nwood, Vernon, Texas, 10\nThe Ni w Mexico Food Products\ncompany of Albuquerque, this week\nf'led articles of incorporation. The\ncapita! stork is given as $25,000 di\nvided into 2500 shares, and the in\ncorporators as G. A. M. Wilson. Al\nhtn;ueroue, 120 shares; Manuel B\nOtero, Albuquerque, 20; E. C. Orteca\nLos Angeles, 20; E. T. Chase, Albu\npteriw, 20; R P. Barnes, Albuquer\nque, 20.\nTh; San Tuan Coal Mining com\npany wh eh is incorporated under\nthe laws of the state of Colorado,\nfil d a fo-risrn corporation's state\nment with the commission in order\n1 1 do b!is;ness in New Mexico. The\nrpnitsl stock of the company is $s0\n000 $42,000 of which has been issued.\nf'':rjt E. Pleasants of Walsenbnre\nColorado, but now Ineatid at the\ncompany's office in Farmincton, is\n'be statutory agent.\nJ S Jabine, now of Trin-d id\nbut form\"rly of this city, was indict\ned this week by the United States\ngrsnd jury on a charge of emhez\nrlonvnt. It is said that he collected\n$125 from a winemaker in San Jmn\ncounty and failed to turn the same\nover to the internal revenue collec\ntor. He states that he recentty\nfni'fd the money in an old grip and\nihrtt failure to turn it ove- was :in\novers ght.\nFollowing is the report of the state\nhealth department for the week\nChickenpox Bernalillo 1. Eddy 2\nSanta Fe 1.\nDiptheria Bernalillo 4, Eddy 9\nLuna 2, Mora 5, San Miguel 2, Union\nGonnorrhea Grant 2, McKinW 1\nTaos 2.\nMeasles Grant 1\nScarlet Fever Eddy 1\nSmallpox Bernal Ho ,1, Roosevelt\nSyphillis Taos 1\nTuberculosis Bernalillo 8. Grant\n5.5. Lincoln 11, Santa Fe. 1.\nTyphoid Fever Bernalillo 3. Mora\n2. San Miguel 3, Santa Fe 9, Socirro\n3\nWhooping Coitah Bernalillo 4\nChaves 1. Eddy 1, Socorro 2\nTHE TAOS COUNTY\nREPUBLICAN TICKET\nFor state senator, Malaquias Mar\ntinez. For representatives, P. V Diek\nman. Urban Ortega.\nFor commissioners, Jose Des\nGeorges, 1st district; C. C. Trujillo.\n2nd district, Max Hartt, 3rd dis\ntrict For sheriff, Manucto O. Trujillo\nFor treasurer, Feder co Trujillo.\nFor county clerk, Esqutpul. Mar\ntinez. For assessor, Elsteo Ortego\nFor probate judge, Benito Chacon.\nFor superintendent of schools,\nCristovil Qumtana.\nFor Surveyor, W. K. Shope.\ni\nCOLFAX COUNTY REPUB\nLICAN CONVENTION\nRATON. Oitober 13 In a conven\ntion marked by complete harmony\nand unanimity of action, and wh ch\nfrequently exhibited great enthus\niasm, the Republicans of Colfav\ncounty placed a full county ticket in\nnomination yesterday afternoon, as\ntoll jws:\nFor State senator, Orie L. Phillips\nof Riton.\nFor representatives in the legisla\nture, Geo. H Webster, Jr. of Cimar\nron and Francisco V gil of Paton\nFir county clerk, Robert L.\nSmith of Raton.\nior sheriff. Abe Hixt tibauh. o'\nRaton.\nI:or superintendent of schools.\nMiss Virginia Reverconb of Chko.\nI 'or probate jiilse, A. C. G-it'errez\nof Raton\nFor assessor, Isaac Littre! of Col-n;o-.\nFor treasurer. Ralph CalVj- of\nSprirger.\nFor Surveyor, Ceo. E. Brgps of\nSprirger.\nFor county commission t, titst\nd f trict, Thos. McBride of Paton.\nFor county commissionr second\ndistrict, C J. Chavez of Dawson.\nFor county commissioner, third\ndistrict, Gib George of Chico.\nThe convention also ratified the\nnomination by the Union c mnty\nRepublicans of Edward M tchell as\njoint senator for the counties oi\nColfax and Union.\nNEW MEXICO\nNEWS REVIEW\nBERNALILLO\nMiss Wilrrra L. Shelton, libraria i\nof the University of New Meat co au\nf ounces that an effort is being made\nto get together a complete collec\ntion of New Mexico history con\nsisting of books, papers, magazines\nreports, pictures, etc., on the history\nrnd description, resources anl in\ndustries, biographits and works of\nNew Mexico authors, art its, musi\ncians, pioneers and early settlers.\nResolutions thanking Joshua Rey\nnolds of Albuquerque for the $5,(JjO.\nK'ft to the home economics depart\nment of the University of New\nMexico were adopted by the student\nbody in assembly at Rodey hall\nFriday morning, at which Mrs Ger\ntrude Martin, secretary of the As\nsociation of Coll.ge Alumni of\nAmerica, was the pr ncipal speaker\nThe McKinley Land and Lumber\ncompany will fight the increased\nfreight rate on logs from Thoreau to\nthe mills at Albuquerque of from\n$-'.50 to $3.12 per 100 feet, which\nwas to have been put in effect Octo\nber 7, Col. George E. Breece prts -dent\nof the company stated.\n\"We have no intention of closing\n'.own the mills and have logs in the\npond now to last us two w.-eks in.\ncase of emergency,\" 'but we will\nnet pay the increased rate. We had\nan agreement sometime ago w th\nthe Santa Fe that the rate on logs\nwould be placed at $250 provided\nwe would keep the mills at Albu\nquerque. We were planning to\nmove them to the mountains neat\n.he timber supply. With th's un\nderstanding we made improvement\nreaching practically $'i)0,000.\"\nThe McKinley company has filed\na formal protest with the corpora\ntion commission at Santa Fe and un\nless the ra Iroad voluntarily re\nstores the old rate the corporation\ncommission will call a hear ng (i..\nHreece said that with the mill run\nning at full capacity, sixty million\nfeel per year, that the new rates\nwould represent an increase of jfM.\n000 in a year's time.\nCHAVES\ni ine of the biggest fires Itoswi II\ncvrr witnessed accurred early Friday\nmen ng, about one-o'cloik, when\nthe round-house, machine-sh ts,\npumping plant and one loco'.rnivt:\nr. the Santa Fe railroad, w.re des\ntroyed in the local yards. The ori\ngin of the fire is not known, but\nwhen discovered the pumping pbm\nwas a mass of flames.\nB. F. Rose, local agent, said that\nbecause of the fact that the build\nings, and the equipment were all\nold, and because the locomotive, or\nswitch engine destroyed was old he\nwould est mate the loss at only\nabout $10,000. Had all been prac\ntically new the loss would have\n1 een at least $40,000 he thinks.\nThe greatest State Convention of\nNew Mexico Baptists opened its\nthree days session in the auditorium\nof the First Baptist Church, of Ros\nwell at 10 o'clock on Tuesday. Octo\nber 12 Messengers from the 175\nBaptist Churches of New Mexico\nrepresenting a membership of about\nten thousand members were in at\ntendance. Dr. Buren Sparks, of Santa Fe,\nwas presiding officer of the Con\nvention at the opening, having serv\ned last vear as the permanent chair\nmap. Mr. Coleman Craig, of Al\nhuqii.rque, is the secretary of the\nconvention and Rev. J. W Bruner\nof Albuquerque is the executive sec\nretary and treasurer.\nThe addresses of welcome were\ndelivered by Tomlinson Fort, repre\ntenting Mayor Rose, in behalf of\nihe city, and Dillard Wyatt n be\nhalf of the local church. Roswcll\nNews\nE A. Wi'kinson, who recently\npurchased 100 acres of land south\neast of Roswell has obtained a per\nmit to have a well drilled thereon\nand is having A. Morris-y, the w-il-known\ndriller do the work.\nJ B. Herbst has on display in this\ncity some of the Durango long sta-\ntie cotton which was grown on the\nInion Central farm near Hagerman.\nThis cotton has be?n pronounced by\nexperts in the valley as being as\nhigh a grade cotton as has ever been\nprown anywh re. The cotton in all\ndetails is perfect At least 70 bah s\nwill be ginned this year from the\nUrioti Central farm. Roswell R c\nord COLFAX\nIt is announced by D. B. Cole, the\nCimarron real estate man, that the\n20.000 acre Rito del Piano ranch\nnrar French in this countv is no v\nbeing cut into tracts of 160 t. fi-iO\naeres and of fired for sile to the\ng-.neral prblic e ther for cash or on\nterm. Th is dcsr-i'ied as sow\nof th finest land in the roimty. w: n\nruntiing water on part of the ran h\nOne of the most interesting events\nnow taking flare in O.-lfax ceun'v\nis the harvesting of the first lart-c\ncommercial crop of appl s from tr.e\noirhai-ds of Ceo H. Webster a'\nCiinaTon One cnrload a day is\nrow coing forward to eastern and\nsouthern points from these f n? or\nchards, and it is exper'ed thn'\ntw.nty-five days w ll be required t\ncomplete the shipments. C H.\nWeaver eV Co. of CHcagi are t e\ndistributors, and McDonald ITa'c. to\ngether wh a co-ps of ten effi tent\npackers and loaders is in charge of\n;he work.\nThe expert pronounce s the fruit\nthe finest in sire and color thev\nhave ever handled, and the fruit\n:t entirely free from blemishes such\nas result from the coddling moth.\nhail, or frost marks. If ore than\n12,000 boxes will be shipped in fan\ncy packs, and less than half of the\norchard is in commercial tearing\nthis year.\n'there is now no ilouht that the\nCimarron district is destined to be\ncome a wonderful fruit section aid\nthe 500 acres now coinpris ng the\nplanted area will rapidly be increas\ned. The Webster orchard, compris\ning about 150 acres, is less than ten\nyears old. Raton Kt.nge.\nCURRY\nThe new $35,000 Baptist Hospital,\nwhich has keen under construction\nfor some time, has been opened. Al\nthough the main floor of the bu lding\nhas not been completed, the second\nf'oor is fin shed and wards are avail\nable for from eight to eleven pa\ntients. Miss Hunter who has been\nconnected with local hospitals for\nsome time will superintend the new\nhospital Clovis News.\nExcavations for the new $sO0Oo.0O\nSanta Fe office building at the fo t\nof Main street are near ng comple\ntion. The new building will occupy\nthe southeast portion of the Harvey\nHouse premises, and will be a two\nstory edifice.\nThe sale of $J3,(Xi00 worth of\nsewer bonds to Bentwell, Phillips,\nEste Co., of Denver, Colorado was\nannounced by the city council as\ncompleted, and the bonds have been\nforwarded to the bond buyers. The\ncouncil then ordered a call for bids\nfor sewer construction cover ng the\nwork contemplated in the bond i\nsu? of last April.\nFollowing up the work of sew\ner extension, the city has ordered\nimmediate sewer taps for all prop\nerty abutting on the city sewer hues\nand property owners have been no\ntified it was stated.\nFailure of legal proceed ngs inci\ndent to the city's paving program\nto meet with the approval of the\nbonding company attorneys because\nof certain discrepancies in connec\ntion with the rate of interest speci\nfied in the procedure, led the coun\ncil to order the retracting of the\nlegal procedure, and possibly a re\nletting of the contract. This, will\nentail a delay of six to eight w.eks\nin clearing up the legal status, and\npaving will not proceed until March\nor April, after freez ng weather has\nrinsed Clovis Journal.\nDONA ANA\nLast Sunday afternoon at 3 o'clock\na congregation convened at the\nschool house at Hill, to take part in\nthe ceremonies attending the laying\nof the cornerstone of a new Episio\npulian church (St. Mary'a-at-HjU.)\nThe services were in charge of\nBishop Howden of Albuquerque, as\nsisted by Rev Hunter I.rwis of St.\nMary's church Mesilla Park, and\nRev. Edw. Doan of St. Andrew's,\nLas Cruccs. Rev. Hunter Lewis\nw II for the present at least, be pa\ntor of the new church.\nContract for the construction of\nthe edifice is expected to be let\nsoon The construction will most\nlikely be of cobblestone, fashioned\naft.r the English style of architec\nture. The congregation will send\nto England for settings of English\nivy to be trained over the church to\ngive it that mellow, un que effect\nthat characterizes the old English\nchurches and cathedrals. Las Cru\nets Republic\nEDDY\nThe new residence of Tom Run\nyan, on Alameda street is about\ncompleted. It is a beautiful home,\none of the finest to be found any\nwhere in the west and nothing has\nbeen slighted in material or labor\nthat would add to its attractive!!. ss\nor convenience.\nMr. and Mrs F. M. Hatf eld r\ntinned from their trip to their old\nhome in Indiana, where they spent\nsix w.eks and returned feeling more\nin love with the valley and her peo\nple thin when they went away.\nSince returning they have sol 1 their\nfarm, one of the best in the vallev\nto a Mr. James who tal.es possession\nthe first of next year. The farm\nhas over one hundred acres of fine\ncotton on it this year and t a valu\nable proposition Carlsbad Curn.nl.\nGRANT 1\nCapt Paul J. Rainey, famous mil\nlionaire and the world's greatest\nlion hunter, arrived in Silver City\nfrom Colorado Sunday with his pack\nbf twenty-three trained fox hounds\nand Airdales and will sp.nd a month\nhunt ng bear in the Black and Mo\ngollon ranges. During Stptember\ntapt. Rainey hunted along the\nWhite River in Colorado, where his\nparty bagg d seven good sized\nbrown and black be.ir. He plans to\nsp nd the m nth of October here\nand left Tttesdav rtnrri\"g wi'h Vic\ntor Culberson for the G. O. S t\nquarters on tlie Sap.ilo from which\npt it he and his party will go into\nthe Clack ranpe an i wrk ti e r way\n-.round into the Mogo'lsn range\nCarta in Ka my is ne of the fore-r-ot\nr a,-.d triners of I lin\ning dogs in the United Sta'es, m;in\ni; \"1 !a-'.;r? l;tni,e:s on his estate\nin Mississippi.\nRa'uey. w''n ?\"-v. 1 as a c-ptnin\nin the Brit sh army d-trt:;? th?\nV-.'r.rl 1 War is a you:-,g rrtsn t! p i i\nhis 44 year, and i- a t.i 1 a'1 i 'e.\nbron7ed by his oiit 'oor 1-fe. He is\na southerner hail n? from Co t n\nPlant, Miss, a srrodl place woi -h\ntakes its rism.- from his plr'ation\nand ranch there. He is trive'rif\nw th a puide. Victor Holmes, and an\nold darkey cook by the rnie of\nJones\nMinirg mm of the state m t in\nthis city Mondav for the ptiToe\norganizing a chapter of the Ameri\ncan Mining Congress and the atten\ndance, was large, showing a healthy\ninterest in the greatest industry in\nthe state.\nThe New Mexico Mining Assoc a-\ntion, organized in this city last Au\ngust, was merged into the great na\ntional mining body and the charter\nmembers of the New Merico chap\nters comprises over fifty Viieuiber\nSilver City Enterprise.\nGUADALUPE\nSher ft J. C. Dunlap arrested and\nlanded in Santa Rosa jail, Thursday\ni evening, Pablo Quintana, 'with three\ndiliereiit charges of running a still,\nj making and selling white mule\"\nwhiskey.\nI The arrest was made twelve miles\nnorth of Cuervo, Guadalupe county,\nat the home of the prisoner, and\nwhere a crude but complete (till was\nfound in operation, together with\nseveral gallons of booze.\nOther arrests wll follow, as tin\nofficers are certain that this has\nbeen the source of supply for \"white\nmule\" which has been so plentiful in\nFort Sumner for the last few mon:hs\nand the sheriff is to be congratu\n1a led on the outcome of his long\nhunt for tli -ulprits -Fort Stimnet\nl.uJ.r.\nLEA\nThe cotton gin at Loviugton which\nhas been in process of erection for\nthe past few weeks, is fast Hearing\nrnmplrt on under the direction oe\nMat Morris.\nBetween thirty and forty bales of\ncotton are in prospect with many\nmore to follow. The first two bales\nbrought to town have been put in\nstorage until the gin is in readiness\nto receive them.\nThe merchants of l.ovington are\ngetting together on a plan to buy\nall the cotton that is brought in and\nwh ch fs for sale at the prevailing\nmarket price which will be received\nby phone each day Lovington\nLeader.\nHIDALGO\nWork is being rushed at the crush\ner at Steins and to that end costly\nequipment is being placed, and when\nfully installed will aid very materi il\nly in turning out many more cars of\nbit last per day\nThe local ore shipments from the\nI ordshurg m ning district for Sen\ntember amounted to eighty nine\ncars, a total of 4,072 tons, with an\napproximate value of $61.00000\nA new strike of very high grade\nfloor spar has been made upon prop\nerty belonging to Billy Smith and\nR. M Reynolds The claim upon\nwhich this find was made lies ad\njoining the tailings pond of the 85\nMine, about three miles south west\nof town. There has not been suf\nficient work done upon the vein as\nyet to he able to t II what the find\nmay amount to, but it will be open\ned ten feet at once. The quality of\nthe fluor spar is very good, it b.ing\n;in unusually d irk green in color and\nwill run 9K per cent calcium fluoride\nThis is the first find of th s sor'\nmade in that section and will en\nrourage further prospecting as\nfluor spar of high grade is in very\nmuch demand. Lordsburg Liberal\nLINCOLN\nR. A. Hunnicutt and son of Capi\nj tan shipped a car load of fat cattle\ni to the El Paso market Wednesday.\nCarrizozo News.\nLUNA\nField Manager F. L. Manlev of\nthe Angelus Oil company has rece v\ned the big rotary rig sent by the\nSouthern California company, which\nhas the drilling contract for the An\ngelus well south of Myndus. to re\nplace the standard rig which was be\ning used on that job. and expects to\nhave the change mide and the new\nrig at woik within the next few\ndays. At a meeting of some 150 Angelus\nstockholders in I os Arg les the lat\nter part of September, an addition\nal block of stock was voted plied\non sale w th the orieinal sto- k\nholders and the entire issue was sub\nscribed by them, thereby continuing\nthe company as a closed corporation.\nAmple funds are at the disposal of\nthis company for prosecuting an\nactive drilling campaign Denting\nHeadlight.\nThe Community Service, Inc., an\nnual meeting and luncheon was held\nrecently at the arm ry. The b.is -oess\nmen of the city and many wo\nmen members of their families at\ntended and enjoyed the very excel\nlent repast provided by the women\nrf the Christian church. Fred\nSherman, chairman of the execu\ntive committee, pn sided. The old\ncommittee consis'insr of Fred SI cr\nman, A A. Temke. Frark NoH'-. i.\nC J. K 11 y. II L HouMcr. C -1--E\nrlc FK- and E R 'a!hn li'h m,\nwas unanimously cho-en to t-.i-re\ncharge of ihe coim-ini v ho-iee r\"d\nthe swimm ng ro\"1 ?.\"d rondii\"! ''e\nactivities of a cot.imur i'm na r r\n1 1 e r orrr 2 vear.\nThe n j o t cf tre s rv f t\nHme!f an J f- 'r-a-:-er. hr,w--1\nth .t tie r-Ti .''i -d r\nrrfriro s t t: !:e VP d'f:.\nhi!'--'\nfj Iff,, f-\nrev' v-T.\ncr ir--\n1TP ,rr.\nloo v i\n-0 r-\nd s f\n.c r,\ni,---1'r. wh:ct r\nto 4 r- :o r-o'e 'h-Ti\nsc\nr.\npr tvMrs for a rfmiT'\npdrpir.istrr.'i'-'n rf sf'-ire\npmwn too 1.-.rre f--e a -rr r\"