overnment. But this\nland is not being worked for coal,\nand the greater part ot it never will\nbe. ihe coal, if any, is thousands\nof feet below the surface of the\nearth, and thousands of acres are to\nclass fkd are many miles in every\nd.rection from railway transporta\ntion. The land has absolutely no\nvalue except fur grazing purposes,\nand in some cases, lor agricultural\npurposes where waur is available\nior irrigation. Land in both San\nJuan and Colfax counties hereto\nfoie classified as \"coal land\" has\nbeen finally reclaimed as agricul\ntural land and properly so. But\nwhat of the laud that can be used\nonly f-r graz ng purposes. What\nwould happen to the homesteaders\nhi San Juan county who are trying\nto hold on until irrigation ditches\nate built. Their lands have been\nclassified as \"coal lands\". Thous\nands of acres oi those lands were\nfiled on before the government is\nsued its patents with coal reserva\ntions. 1 lie democrats insist that non-productive\ncoal-lands'' be assessed\nhigher.\nLive us the figures, gentlemen?\nTell the taxpayers just what kind of\nl.gislation you are going to enact,\nif elected? Jumping on one or\ntwo corporations don't alter the\nfact that hundreds of citizens of\nthis state are vitally concerned\nWhat are you going to do to them\nIn San Juan county some of this\n\"coal land\" has been assessed at a\nhigh rate The taxes thereon have\nremained unpaid for several years\nA lot of the land has been sold for\ntaxes. No man can afford to keep\nit, waiting for ditches to be con\nstructed. It s not valuable fot\ncoal. It is grazing land only and\nlocated in a section having but half\nthe annual rainfall that comes to\nseme of the eastern counties.\nThe plain fact is that the demo\ncats have no idea of the resulis ot\nsome of their taxation srhemcs pro\nposed in general terms Take the\nCu.-t of \"contiguous lands\" te the\nworking coal in in;; it includes all\nunproductive coal lands owned b\nthe worling m nc classified as\n\